        "paragraphs": [
          "When Fatima was studying for her university exams last month, she was *struggling* with memorizing difficult concepts. Her grandmother advised her to get more sleep, saying it would help her brain *process* the information better. At first, Fatima thought this was just old wisdom, but scientific research proves that her grandmother was absolutely right.",
          "While we are sleeping peacefully, our brains are actually working harder than we might imagine. Scientists have discovered that during sleep, the brain *sorts through* all the information from the day and decides what to keep and what to forget. This process is called memory *consolidation*, and it happens primarily during deep sleep phases. Dr. Sarah Ahmed, a neuroscientist at King Abdulaziz University, explains that students who sleep for 7-8 hours after studying *perform* significantly better on tests compared to those who stay awake all night.",
          "The brain also uses sleep time to *clear out* waste products that build up during waking hours. Researchers at New York University found that the brain's cleaning system becomes 60% more active during sleep. This process helps *prevent* memory problems and keeps our minds sharp. When we don't get enough sleep, these waste products *accumulate* in the brain, making it harder to *concentrate* and remember new information.",
          "Interestingly, different types of memories are *strengthened* during different sleep stages. Skills like playing the oud or typing on a computer improve during light sleep, while factual information like vocabulary words and historical dates are better *retained* during deep sleep. This is why many successful students in Riyadh and Jeddah have started following a regular sleep schedule before important exams.",
          "Next time you're tempted to *stay up* all night studying, remember Fatima's grandmother's advice. Your brain needs sleep to organize and strengthen memories effectively. Getting proper rest isn't being lazy—it's giving your mind the time it needs to work its magic."
        ]
      },
