    {
      "id": "a211d142-39ba-49f3-84e5-74edf7cc4007",
      "level_number": 2,
      "passage_content": {
        "paragraphs": [
          "Every morning when Fatima wakes up in her apartment in Riyadh, her brain is already working hard to *process* thousands of pieces of information. While she was sleeping, her mind was *organizing* the events from the previous day, deciding which memories to keep and which ones to *forget*. This amazing process happens automatically, but scientists are still trying to *understand* exactly how our brains manage this incredible task.",
          "The human brain contains approximately 86 billion neurons, and each neuron can *connect* with thousands of others. When we experience something new, these neurons *work together* to create what researchers call a memory trace. Dr. Sarah Johnson, a neuroscientist at King Abdullah University of Science and Technology, explains that our brains are constantly *making decisions* about what information is important. \"When students are *studying* for exams, their brains are actually building stronger connections between neurons,\" she says. \"The more they review the material, the stronger these connections become.\"",
          "Interestingly, our memories are not stored in just one place in the brain. Instead, different types of memories live in different areas. The hippocampus, a small seahorse-shaped structure, helps us *remember* facts and events from our daily lives. Meanwhile, the cerebellum stores our muscle memories – like how to ride a bicycle or write Arabic calligraphy. When we *recall* a memory, our brain brings together information from multiple areas, almost like assembling pieces of a puzzle.",
          "Scientists have discovered that we can actually improve our memory abilities through practice and healthy habits. Regular exercise increases blood flow to the brain, while getting enough sleep helps the brain *consolidate* memories from the day. Many Islamic scholars throughout history understood this connection – they often recommended morning study sessions when the mind was fresh and clear. Research shows that people who *practice* memory techniques, such as creating mental images or telling stories, can remember up to 40% more information than those who simply repeat facts.",
          "Today, as we live in an age of smartphones and digital devices, some people worry that we are becoming too dependent on technology to remember things for us. However, neuroscientists believe that our brains are simply adapting to new challenges, just as they have done throughout human history."
        ]
      },
